  <description type="morphology">Shrubs, 30–100 cm. Stems sparsely short-hispidulous. Leaves sessile; blades obovate to oblong, 15–25 × 5–12 mm, coriaceous, bases subclasping, margins coarsely spinulose-dentate or -serrate (with 5–11 pairs of teeth), faces glabrous. Heads in densely spiciform arrays. Involucres cuneate to very narrowly turbinate, 10–17 × 3–6 mm. Phyllaries stiffly erect, almost completely stramineous, linear-lanceolate, faces glabrous except minutely gland-dotted at tips. Ray florets 0. Disc florets 4–8(–10); corollas 7–9 mm. Cypselae 5–8 mm, glabrous. 2n = 10.</description>
  <description type="phenology">Flowering Sep–Nov.</description>
  <description type="habitat">Oak-pine woods;</description>
  <description type="elevation">150–2000 m;</description>
  <description type="distribution">Calif.; Mexico (Baja California).</description>
  <number>2.</number>
  <other_name type="common_name">Serpentine bristleweed</other_name>
  <discussion>Hazardia stenolepis is distinguished by its hairy stems, glabrous, relatively small leaves, discoid heads, and long, narrow involucres with stramineous, linear-lanceolate phyllaries.</discussion>
